.TH inet_res 3 "kernel 10.6.1" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
inet_res \- A rudimentary DNS client.

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
This module performs DNS name resolving towards recursive name servers.

.PP
See also ERTS User's Guide: Inet Configuration or more information about how to configure an Erlang runtime system for IP communication, and how to enable this DNS client by defining \fI'dns'\fR as a lookup method. The DNS client then acts as a backend for the resolving functions in \fIinet\fR.

.PP
This DNS client can resolve DNS records even if it is not used for normal name resolving in the node.

.PP
This is not a full-fledged resolver, only a DNS client that relies on asking trusted recursive name servers.

.SS "Name Resolving"

.PP
UDP queries are used unless resolver option \fIusevc\fR is \fItrue\fR, which forces TCP queries.  If the query is too large for UDP, TCP is used instead. For regular DNS queries, 512 bytes is the size limit.

.PP
When EDNS is enabled (resolver option \fIedns\fR is set to the EDNS version (that is; \fI0\fR instead of \fIfalse\fR), resolver option \fIudp_payload_size\fR sets the payload size limit.  If a name server replies with the TC bit set (truncation), indicating that the answer is incomplete, the query is retried towards the same name server using TCP.  Resolver option \fIudp_payload_size\fR also sets the advertised size for the maximum allowed reply size, if EDNS is enabled, otherwise the name server uses the limit 512 bytes. If the reply is larger, it gets truncated, forcing a TCP requery.

.PP
For UDP queries, resolver options \fItimeout\fR and \fIretry\fR control retransmission.  Each name server in the \fInameservers\fR list is tried with a time-out of \fItimeout\fR/\fIretry\fR. Then all name servers are tried again, doubling the time-out, for a total of \fIretry\fR times.

.PP
But before all name servers are tried again, there is a (user configurable) time-out, \fIservfail_retry_timeout\fR. The point of this is to prevent the new query to be handled by a server's servfail cache (a client that is too eager will actually only get what is in the servfail cache). If there is too little time left of the resolver call's time-out to do a retry, the resolver call may return before the call's time-out has expired.

.PP
For queries not using the \fIsearch\fR list, if the query to all \fInameservers\fR results in \fI{error,nxdomain}\fR or an empty answer, the same query is tried for \fIalt_nameservers\fR.

